{
  "version": "2.1.0",
  "$schema": "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/oasis-tcs/sarif-spec/main/sarif-2.1/schema/sarif-schema-2.1.0.json",
  "runs": [
    {
      "tool": {
        "driver": {
          "informationUri": "https://github.com/DataDog/datadog-saist",
          "name": "datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
          "rules": [
            {
              "id": "datadog/csharp-accesscontrol",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential improper access control"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In C#, Improper Access Control (CWE-284) occurs when user input (such as IDs or identifiers) is used to\naccess resources without verifying ownership or permissions (IDOR).\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```csharp\nint docId = int.Parse(Request.QueryString[\"doc_id\"]);\nvar doc = dbContext.Documents.Find(docId);\n// No ownership check!\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Always verify resource ownership before returning data.\n- Use WHERE clauses that include the current user's ID.\n- Implement authorization middleware for sensitive operations."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:284",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/csharp-brokencrypto",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential use of broken cryptography"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In C#, Broken Cryptography (CWE-327) occurs when weak algorithms, modes, or key management\npractices are used to encrypt sensitive input.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```csharp\nusing var des = DES.Create();  // DES is weak\nusing var aes = Aes.Create();\naes.Mode = CipherMode.ECB;  // ECB mode is weak\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Use Aes with GCM mode for authenticated encryption.\n- Use RandomNumberGenerator for random number generation.\n- Never hardcode keys or use static IVs."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:327",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/csharp-cmdi",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential command injection"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In C#, Command Injection (CWE-77) occurs when untrusted input is passed to system commands,\noften via Process.Start with shell execution or string concatenation, allowing arbitrary command execution.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```csharp\nstring userInput = Request.QueryString[\"cmd\"];\nProcess.Start(\"cmd.exe\", \"/c \" + userInput);\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Avoid shells; use ProcessStartInfo with ArgumentList:\n```csharp\nvar psi = new ProcessStartInfo(\"myapp.exe\");\npsi.ArgumentList.Add(userInput);\nProcess.Start(psi);\n```\n- Validate/allowlist inputs before passing as arguments.\n- Prefer .NET APIs to perform system tasks instead of shelling out."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:78",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/csharp-codei",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential code injection"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In C#, Code Injection (CWE-94) occurs when untrusted input is used in dynamic code compilation,\nRoslyn scripting, or reflection-based invocation.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```csharp\nstring code = Request.Form[\"code\"];\nvar result = CSharpScript.EvaluateAsync(code).Result;\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Never pass user input to CSharpScript or dynamic compilation.\n- Use pre-compiled code paths; avoid runtime code generation.\n- Validate assembly/type names against strict allowlists."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:94",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/csharp-deserialization",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential insecure deserialization"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In C#, Insecure Deserialization (CWE-502) occurs when untrusted input is deserialized\nusing dangerous formatters like BinaryFormatter, allowing arbitrary code execution.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```csharp\nvar formatter = new BinaryFormatter();\nobject obj = formatter.Deserialize(stream);  // RCE risk!\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Avoid BinaryFormatter, SoapFormatter, NetDataContractSerializer with untrusted data.\n- Use System.Text.Json or JsonSerializer which are safer.\n- If binary serialization is required, use sealed types and validation."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:502",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/csharp-insecurecookie",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential insecure cookie configuration"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In C#, Insecure Cookie (CWE-614) occurs when cookies storing sensitive input (session tokens, auth data)\nare created without proper security attributes (Secure, HttpOnly, SameSite).\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```csharp\nvar cookie = new HttpCookie(\"SessionId\", sessionId);\nResponse.Cookies.Add(cookie);  // Missing Secure, HttpOnly, SameSite\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Set Secure = true for HTTPS-only transmission.\n- Set HttpOnly = true to prevent JavaScript access.\n- Set SameSite = SameSiteMode.Strict for CSRF protection."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:614",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/csharp-ldapi",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential LDAP injection"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In C#, LDAP Injection (CWE-90) occurs when untrusted input is used to construct LDAP queries,\nallowing attackers to modify queries or access unauthorized directory data.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```csharp\nstring filter = $\"(\u0026(uid={username})(objectClass=user))\";\nvar searcher = new DirectorySearcher(entry, filter);\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Escape special LDAP characters in user input (*, (, ), \\, NUL).\n- Validate and sanitize input with allowlists.\n- Use parameterized LDAP queries where available."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:90",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/csharp-pathtraversal",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential path traversal"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In C#, Path Traversal (CWE-22) occurs when untrusted input is used to construct file paths,\nallowing attackers to access files outside the intended directory.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```csharp\nstring filename = Request.QueryString[\"file\"];\nstring content = File.ReadAllText(Path.Combine(\"/var/data/\", filename));\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Use Path.GetFullPath and verify the path stays within the base directory.\n- Validate filenames against allowlists.\n- Reject paths containing \"..\" or absolute paths."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:22",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/csharp-promptinjection",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential prompt injection"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In C#, Prompt Injection (CWE-1427) occurs when untrusted user input is concatenated directly into LLM prompts, allowing attackers to manipulate AI behavior, bypass safety guardrails, or extract sensitive information.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```csharp\nstring userMessage = Request.Query[\"message\"];\nstring prompt = \"You are a helpful assistant. User says: \" + userMessage;\nvar chatCompletionsOptions = new ChatCompletionsOptions\n{\n    Messages = { new ChatMessage(ChatRole.System, prompt) }\n};\nawait client.GetChatCompletionsAsync(\"gpt-4\", chatCompletionsOptions);\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Use structured message formats with separate system/user roles\n- Validate and sanitize user input before inclusion in prompts\n- Use Semantic Kernel with proper prompt templates\n- Apply input allowlists and output filtering\n- Never concatenate user input directly into system prompts"
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:1427",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/csharp-sqli",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential SQL injection"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In C#, SQL Injection (CWE-89) happens when user input is used directly in SQL queries without proper escaping, \nallowing attackers to alter or query data maliciously.\n\nTo prevent SQL injection, use parameterized queries or Entity Framework's LINQ methods.\n\nFor example, instead of:\n```csharp\nstring query = $\"SELECT * FROM Users WHERE Username='{username}'\";\nvar cmd = new SqlCommand(query, connection);\n```\n\nUse:\n```csharp\nvar cmd = new SqlCommand(\"SELECT * FROM Users WHERE Username = @username\", connection);\ncmd.Parameters.AddWithValue(\"@username\", username);\n```\n\nAlways validate inputs and avoid building SQL statements through string concatenation or interpolation."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:89",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/csharp-trustboundary",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential trust boundary violation"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In C#, Trust Boundary Violation (CWE-501) occurs when untrusted user input is stored in trusted\nstorage (session, cache) and later used for security decisions without validation.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```csharp\nstring role = Request.Form[\"role\"];\nSession[\"UserRole\"] = role;  // User controls their own role!\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Never store user-controlled data in session for authorization without validation.\n- Look up roles/permissions from trusted sources (database).\n- Validate against strict allowlists before storing."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:501",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/csharp-weakhash",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential use of weak hash algorithm"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In C#, Weak Hash (CWE-328) occurs when cryptographically broken hash algorithms like MD5 or SHA-1\nare used to hash sensitive input such as passwords or to generate digital signatures.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```csharp\nusing var md5 = MD5.Create();\nbyte[] hash = md5.ComputeHash(Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(password));\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Use BCrypt, Argon2, or PBKDF2 for password hashing.\n- Use SHA-256 or SHA-512 for general cryptographic hashing.\n- MD5/SHA-1 are acceptable for non-security purposes (checksums, cache keys)."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:328",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/csharp-weakrandomness",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential use of weak randomness"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In C#, Weak Randomness (CWE-330) occurs when System.Random is used to generate input for security-sensitive\noperations like tokens, passwords, session IDs, or cryptographic keys.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```csharp\nvar rand = new Random();\nstring token = rand.Next().ToString();\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Use RandomNumberGenerator for security-sensitive random generation.\n- System.Random is acceptable for non-security purposes (shuffling, tests, simulations).\n- Use RandomNumberGenerator.GetBytes() for secure random bytes."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:330",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/csharp-xpathi",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential XPath injection"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In C#, XPath Injection (CWE-91) occurs when untrusted input is inserted into XPath queries\nwithout validation, allowing attackers to modify XML data queries or bypass authentication.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```csharp\nstring expr = $\"//user[name/text()='{input}']\";\nvar nodes = doc.SelectNodes(expr);\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Avoid constructing XPath expressions with user-controlled data.\n- Use XPathExpression.Compile with variables or escape values.\n- Validate and sanitize input before building expressions.\n- Restrict XPath queries to expected structures."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:643",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/csharp-xss",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential cross-site scripting"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In C# web apps (ASP.NET), Cross-Site Scripting (CWE-79) occurs when untrusted input is rendered into responses\nwithout proper output encoding, enabling execution of attacker-controlled scripts.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```csharp\nResponse.Write(\"\u003cp\u003e\" + Request.QueryString[\"q\"] + \"\u003c/p\u003e\");\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Use Razor views which auto-encode by default (@Model.Property).\n- Apply HttpUtility.HtmlEncode or WebUtility.HtmlEncode for manual encoding.\n- Validate inputs and avoid reflecting raw parameters.\n- Consider enabling Content Security Policy (CSP)."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:79",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/go-accesscontrol",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential improper access control"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Go, Improper Access Control (CWE-284) occurs when user input (such as IDs or identifiers) is used to\naccess resources without verifying ownership or permissions (IDOR).\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```go\ndocID := r.URL.Query().Get(\"doc_id\")\ndoc, _ := db.Query(\"SELECT * FROM documents WHERE id = ?\", docID)\n// No ownership check!\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Always verify resource ownership before returning data.\n- Use WHERE clauses that include the current user's ID.\n- Implement authorization middleware for sensitive operations."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:284",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/go-brokencrypto",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential use of broken cryptography"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Go, Broken Cryptography (CWE-327) occurs when weak algorithms, modes, or key management\npractices are used to encrypt sensitive input.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```go\nblock, _ := des.NewCipher(key)  // DES is weak\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Use AES with GCM mode for authenticated encryption.\n- Use crypto/rand for random number generation.\n- Never hardcode keys or use static IVs.\n- Use RSA with key size \u003e= 2048 bits."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:327",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/go-cmdi",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential command injection"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Go, Command Injection (CWE-77) occurs when untrusted input is passed to system commands,\noften via exec.Command with \"sh -c\" or string concatenation, allowing arbitrary command execution.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```go\ncmd := exec.Command(\"sh\", \"-c\", \"ls \" + userInput)\n_ = cmd.Run()\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Avoid shells like \"sh -c\"; use exec.Command with fixed arguments:\n```go\ncmd := exec.Command(\"ls\", userInput)\n```\n- Validate/allowlist inputs before passing as arguments.\n- Prefer native Go APIs to perform system tasks instead of shelling out."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:78",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/go-codei",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential code injection"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Go, Code Injection (CWE-94) occurs when untrusted input is used in template parsing,\nplugin loading, or dynamic code execution.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```go\ntemplateStr := r.FormValue(\"template\")\ntmpl, _ := template.New(\"user\").Parse(templateStr)\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Use pre-compiled templates; don't parse user-controlled strings.\n- Validate plugin paths against allowlists.\n- Use html/template which auto-escapes by default."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:94",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/go-deserialization",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential insecure deserialization"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Go, Insecure Deserialization (CWE-502) occurs when untrusted input is deserialized using\ndangerous formats like encoding/gob or gopkg.in/yaml.v2.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```go\ndecoder := gob.NewDecoder(r.Body)\nvar data interface{}\ndecoder.Decode(\u0026data)  // Gob can execute code during deserialization\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Avoid gob with untrusted input; use JSON with concrete types.\n- Use yaml.v3 instead of yaml.v2.\n- Only deserialize from trusted sources."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:502",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/go-insecurecookie",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential insecure cookie configuration"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Go, Insecure Cookie (CWE-614) occurs when cookies storing sensitive input (session tokens, auth data)\nare created without proper security attributes (Secure, HttpOnly, SameSite).\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```go\ncookie := \u0026http.Cookie{Name: \"session_id\", Value: sessionID}\nhttp.SetCookie(w, cookie)  // Missing Secure, HttpOnly, SameSite\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Set Secure: true for HTTPS-only transmission.\n- Set HttpOnly: true to prevent JavaScript access.\n- Set SameSite: http.SameSiteStrictMode for CSRF protection."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:614",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/go-ldapi",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential LDAP injection"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Go, LDAP Injection (CWE-90) occurs when untrusted input is used to construct LDAP queries,\nallowing attackers to modify queries or access unauthorized directory data.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```go\nfilter := fmt.Sprintf(\"(\u0026(uid=%s)(objectClass=user))\", username)\nconn.Search(ldap.NewSearchRequest(baseDN, ldap.ScopeWholeSubtree, 0, 0, 0, false, filter, nil, nil))\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Use ldap.EscapeFilter() to escape user input in LDAP filters.\n- Validate and sanitize input with allowlists.\n- Use parameterized LDAP queries where available."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:90",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/go-pathtraversal",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential path traversal"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Go, Path Traversal (CWE-22) occurs when untrusted input is used to construct file paths,\nallowing attackers to access files outside the intended directory.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```go\nfilename := r.URL.Query().Get(\"file\")\ndata, _ := os.ReadFile(\"/var/data/\" + filename)\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Use filepath.Clean and verify the path stays within the base directory.\n- Validate filenames against allowlists.\n- Reject paths containing \"..\" or absolute paths."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:22",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/go-promptinjection",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential prompt injection"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Go, Prompt Injection (CWE-1427) occurs when untrusted user input is concatenated directly into LLM prompts, allowing attackers to manipulate AI behavior, bypass safety guardrails, or extract sensitive information.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```go\nuserMessage := r.FormValue(\"message\")\nprompt := \"You are a helpful assistant. User says: \" + userMessage\nresponse := client.CreateChatCompletion(ctx, openai.ChatCompletionRequest{\n    Model: openai.GPT4,\n    Messages: []openai.ChatCompletionMessage{\n        {Role: \"system\", Content: prompt},\n    },\n})\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Use structured message formats with separate system/user roles\n- Validate and sanitize user input before inclusion in prompts\n- Implement prompt injection detection patterns\n- Apply input allowlists and output filtering\n- Never concatenate user input directly into system prompts"
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:1427",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/go-sqli",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential SQL injection"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Go, SQL Injection (CWE-89) happens when user input is used directly in SQL queries without proper escaping, \nallowing attackers to alter or query data maliciously.\n\nTo prevent SQL injection, use parameterized queries or the database/sql package's query methods \nthat support placeholders.\n\nFor example, instead of:\n```go\nquery := fmt.Sprintf(\"SELECT * FROM users WHERE username='%s'\", username)\nrows, _ := db.Query(query)\n```\n\nUse:\n```go\nrows, _ := db.Query(\"SELECT * FROM users WHERE username = ?\", username)\n```\n\nAlways validate inputs and avoid building SQL statements through string concatenation or formatting."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:89",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/go-trustboundary",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential trust boundary violation"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Go, Trust Boundary Violation (CWE-501) occurs when untrusted user input is stored in trusted\nstorage (session, context) and later used for security decisions without validation.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```go\nrole := r.FormValue(\"role\")\nsession.Values[\"userRole\"] = role  // User controls their own role!\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Never store user-controlled data in session for authorization without validation.\n- Look up roles/permissions from trusted sources (database).\n- Validate against strict allowlists before storing."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:501",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/go-weakhash",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential use of weak hash algorithm"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Go, Weak Hash (CWE-328) occurs when cryptographically broken hash algorithms like MD5 or SHA-1\nare used to hash sensitive input such as passwords or to generate digital signatures.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```go\nhash := md5.Sum([]byte(password))\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Use bcrypt, argon2, or scrypt for password hashing.\n- Use SHA-256 or SHA-512 for general cryptographic hashing.\n- MD5/SHA-1 are acceptable for non-security purposes (checksums, cache keys)."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:328",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/go-weakrandomness",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential use of weak randomness"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Go, Weak Randomness (CWE-330) occurs when math/rand is used to generate input for security-sensitive\noperations like tokens, passwords, session IDs, or cryptographic keys.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```go\ntoken := make([]byte, 16)\nfor i := range token {\n    token[i] = byte(rand.Intn(256))\n}\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Use crypto/rand for security-sensitive random generation.\n- math/rand is acceptable for non-security purposes (shuffling, tests, simulations).\n- Use rand.Read() from crypto/rand for secure random bytes."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:330",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/go-xpathi",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential XPath injection"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Go, XPath Injection (CWE-91) occurs when untrusted input is inserted into XPath queries\nwithout validation, allowing attackers to modify XML data queries or bypass authentication.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```go\nexpr := fmt.Sprintf(\"//user[name/text()='%s']\", input)\nresult := xpath.Evaluate(expr, doc)\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Avoid constructing XPath expressions with user-controlled data.\n- Use libraries or APIs that safely bind parameters or escape values.\n- Validate and sanitize input before building expressions.\n- Restrict XPath queries to expected structures."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:643",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/go-xss",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential cross-site scripting"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Go web apps, Cross-Site Scripting (CWE-79) occurs when untrusted input is rendered into responses\nwithout proper output encoding, enabling execution of attacker-controlled scripts.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```go\nfmt.Fprintf(w, \"\u003cp\u003e%s\u003c/p\u003e\", r.FormValue(\"q\"))\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Use html/template (not text/template) which auto-escapes by context.\n- Apply the correct escaping for the output context (HTML, URL, JS).\n- Validate inputs and avoid reflecting raw parameters.\n- Consider enabling Content Security Policy (CSP)."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:79",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/java-accesscontrol",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential improper access control"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Java, Improper Access Control (CWE-284) occurs when user input (such as IDs or identifiers) is used to access resources\nwithout ownership verification (IDOR).\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```java\nLong id = Long.parseLong(request.getParameter(\"id\"));\nDocument doc = documentRepository.findById(id).orElseThrow();\n// No ownership check!\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Use @PreAuthorize annotations for method-level security.\n- Verify resource.getOwner().equals(currentUser) before returning.\n- Use repository methods that filter by current user."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:284",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/java-brokencrypto",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential use of broken cryptography"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Java, Broken Cryptography (CWE-327) occurs when weak algorithms, modes, or key management\npractices are used to encrypt sensitive input.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```java\nCipher cipher = Cipher.getInstance(\"DES\");  // Weak algorithm\nCipher cipher = Cipher.getInstance(\"AES/ECB/PKCS5Padding\");  // Weak mode\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Use AES/GCM/NoPadding for authenticated encryption.\n- Use SecureRandom for random number generation.\n- Never hardcode keys or use static IVs."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:327",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/java-cmdi",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential command injection"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Java, Command Injection (CWE-77) occurs when untrusted input is used to build OS command strings,\nallowing attackers to execute arbitrary system commands. This typically involves misuse of Runtime.exec()\nor ProcessBuilder with concatenated strings.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```java\nRuntime.getRuntime().exec(\"ls \" + userInput);\n```\n\nIf 'userInput' contains shell metacharacters, attackers can chain additional commands.\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Avoid building shell commands with string concatenation.\n- Prefer ProcessBuilder with fixed argument arrays:\n```java\nnew ProcessBuilder(\"ls\", userInput).start();\n```\n- Strictly validate and sanitize inputs (allowlists where possible).\n- Prefer built-in APIs (file I/O, libraries) instead of shelling out."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:78",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/java-codei",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential code injection"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Java, Code Injection (CWE-94) occurs when untrusted input is evaluated as code via\nscripting engines, expression languages, or dynamic class loading.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```java\nScriptEngine engine = new ScriptEngineManager().getEngineByName(\"JavaScript\");\nengine.eval(request.getParameter(\"script\"));\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Never pass user input to ScriptEngine.eval() or SpEL.\n- Use SimpleEvaluationContext for restricted SpEL evaluation.\n- Validate class names against strict allowlists."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:94",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/java-deserialization",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential insecure deserialization"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Java, Insecure Deserialization (CWE-502) occurs when untrusted input is deserialized\nusing ObjectInputStream, allowing arbitrary code execution.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```java\nObjectInputStream ois = new ObjectInputStream(request.getInputStream());\nObject obj = ois.readObject();  // RCE via gadget chains!\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Avoid ObjectInputStream with untrusted data.\n- Use ObjectInputFilter (Java 9+) with strict allowlists.\n- Use JSON/Jackson without enableDefaultTyping()."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:502",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/java-insecurecookie",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential insecure cookie configuration"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Java, Insecure Cookie (CWE-614) occurs when cookies storing sensitive input lack security\nattributes like setSecure(), setHttpOnly(), or SameSite.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```java\nCookie cookie = new Cookie(\"SESSIONID\", sessionId);\nresponse.addCookie(cookie);  // Missing security attributes\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Call setSecure(true) for HTTPS-only transmission.\n- Call setHttpOnly(true) to prevent JavaScript access.\n- Set SameSite attribute for CSRF protection."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:614",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/java-ldapi",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential LDAP injection"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Java, LDAP Injection (CWE-90) occurs when untrusted input is embedded into LDAP queries,\nallowing attackers to modify directory queries or access unauthorized data.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```java\nString filter = \"(\u0026(uid=\" + username + \")(objectClass=user))\";\nctx.search(baseDN, filter, searchControls);\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Use Spring's LdapEncoder.filterEncode() or similar escaping.\n- Use parameterized LDAP queries with LdapQueryBuilder.\n- Validate input against strict allowlists."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:90",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/java-pathtraversal",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential path traversal"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Java, Path Traversal (CWE-22) occurs when untrusted input is used to construct file paths,\nallowing attackers to access or modify files outside the intended directory.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```java\nString filename = request.getParameter(\"file\");\nFile file = new File(\"/var/data/\" + filename);\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Use Path.normalize() and verify with startsWith() against base directory.\n- Use FilenameUtils.getName() to extract only the filename.\n- Validate against allowlists or reject \"..\" sequences."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:22",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/java-promptinjection",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential prompt injection"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Java, Prompt Injection (CWE-1427) occurs when untrusted user input is concatenated directly into LLM prompts, allowing attackers to manipulate AI behavior, bypass safety guardrails, or extract sensitive information.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```java\nString userMessage = request.getParameter(\"message\");\nString prompt = \"You are a helpful assistant. User says: \" + userMessage;\nChatCompletionRequest req = ChatCompletionRequest.builder()\n    .model(\"gpt-4\")\n    .messages(List.of(new ChatMessage(\"system\", prompt)))\n    .build();\nclient.createChatCompletion(req);\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Use structured message formats with separate system/user roles\n- Validate and sanitize user input before inclusion in prompts\n- Use LangChain4j or Spring AI with proper template systems\n- Apply input allowlists and output filtering\n- Never concatenate user input directly into system prompts"
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:1427",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/java-sqli",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential SQL injection"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Java, SQL Injection (CWE-89) occurs when untrusted input is concatenated directly into SQL statements, \nallowing attackers to manipulate queries or access sensitive data. This can lead to data leaks or full \ndatabase compromise.\n\nTo prevent SQL injection, always use parameterized queries or prepared statements instead of string concatenation.\n\nFor example, instead of:\n```java\nStatement stmt = conn.createStatement();\nResultSet rs = stmt.executeQuery(\"SELECT * FROM users WHERE username='\" + username + \"'\");\n```\n\nUse:\n```java\nPreparedStatement ps = conn.prepareStatement(\"SELECT * FROM users WHERE username = ?\");\nps.setString(1, username);\nResultSet rs = ps.executeQuery();\n```\n\nValidate and sanitize user inputs, and prefer ORM frameworks like Hibernate or JPA that handle \nquery parameters safely."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:89",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/java-trustboundary",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential trust boundary violation"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Java, Trust Boundary Violation (CWE-501) occurs when untrusted user input is stored in HttpSession\nor security context and used for authorization without proper validation.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```java\nString role = request.getParameter(\"role\");\nsession.setAttribute(\"userRole\", role);\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Never trust user input for security-sensitive session data.\n- Look up roles from authenticated user in database.\n- Use Spring Security's managed authentication context."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:501",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/java-weakhash",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential use of weak hash algorithm"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Java, Weak Hash (CWE-328) occurs when broken algorithms like MD5 or SHA-1 are used to\nhash sensitive input such as passwords or to generate signatures.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```java\nMessageDigest md = MessageDigest.getInstance(\"MD5\");\nbyte[] hash = md.digest(password.getBytes());\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Use BCryptPasswordEncoder or Argon2PasswordEncoder for passwords.\n- Use SHA-256 or SHA-512 for general hashing.\n- MD5/SHA-1 are acceptable for non-security purposes."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:328",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
